VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Dance releases a free video generator where you can just upload a photo of anyone and make them do anything. Plus, they\'ve released the most realistic lipsync animator tool you can use right now. This AI can segment 3D models and'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reconstruct each individual part and a lot more. So, let\'s jump right in. First up, this AI is a different way to create videos. So, it\'s called video from 3D.'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here\'s how it works. This basically takes in an image of what you want to generate plus a moving 3D model of that object or scene and it would generate a video from that. So, it\'s basically'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'applying the texture and surfaces and colors from your reference style onto the 3D model. And this gives you precise camera control over how you want to move around in the scene or how the objects'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'should move in the scene because you\'re controlling this from the 3D generation. So, here are some other examples for your reference. Notice that your style image doesn\'t have to exactly match your 3D model. It\'s just applying that'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'artistic style to the 3D model. For example, notice that the roof of the reference building is not the same as your 3D model. And also note here that you can prompt it further to add different effects to the video. So, for'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example, you can change the season or time of day just with a simple prompt. Or you can also add visual effects such as fire like this. Now, if you compare this with other similar tools, notice'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that this new one, video from 3D, is just a lot more consistent, whereas the other tools often hallucinate a lot and they get the details wrong. So, here\'s how it works. It would take in your'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference plus it seems like the edge or cany map of your video and then it would go through two different modules. The first one is this SAG module, which stands for sparse anchor view generation. And this basically generates a few frames or anchor views which it'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will use as references. And then it will plug these frames through this GGI module which stands for geometry guided generative inbetweening. And this basically interpolates all the frames in'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'between these anchor views or basically fills in the blanks to smoothly create your final video. Anyways, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo and this contains all the instructions on how to install'

